WEBVTT

00:01.736 --> 00:04.169
The shocking crime
that rocked Hollywood...

00:05.572 --> 00:07.705
She was Hollywood's golden girl.

00:07.707 --> 00:10.008
She was the first bombshell.

00:10.010 --> 00:12.944
...a future president
in a Wild-West showdown...

00:13.414 --> 00:15.680
PORGES: He wants to capture
these men alive

00:15.682 --> 00:17.649
and try them for their crimes.

00:18.719 --> 00:22.354
...and a nuclear nightmare in
the skies over North Carolina.

00:23.423 --> 00:25.791
BAILEY: This was going to be
the deadliest accident

00:25.793 --> 00:27.393
in American history.

00:28.895 --> 00:31.096
These are the
"Mysteries at the Museum."

00:31.098 --> 00:36.701
♪♪

00:36.703 --> 00:41.106
In 1945, the first
nuclear device was detonated

00:41.108 --> 00:43.976
in New Mexico's
Jornada del Muerto desert.

00:45.212 --> 00:48.046
And north of the test site
in the city of Albuquerque

00:48.048 --> 00:52.584
is an institution dedicated
to this explosive history --

00:52.586 --> 00:55.654
the National Museum of
Nuclear Science & History.

00:55.656 --> 01:02.193
♪♪

01:02.195 --> 01:04.396
The collection includes
a replica

01:04.398 --> 01:06.698
of the first atomic bomb
to be tested,

01:06.700 --> 01:08.967
nicknamed "Gadget,"

01:08.969 --> 01:12.571
a nuclear weapon that could be
launched from a jet fighter,

01:12.573 --> 01:14.706
and an intercontinental
ballistic missile

01:14.708 --> 01:18.009
dating back to 1958,
known as "Thor."

01:18.011 --> 01:20.546
♪♪

01:20.548 --> 01:22.647
But among these powerful devices

01:22.649 --> 01:25.551
is one that looks
deceptively simple.

01:25.553 --> 01:28.086
BAILEY:
The artifact is shaped
like a toaster.

01:28.088 --> 01:31.557
It's about 10 inches tall
and 10 inches wide.

01:31.559 --> 01:33.625
There are toggles
and indicator lights.

01:33.627 --> 01:36.895
There's no way of knowing
exactly what it's for.

01:39.366 --> 01:41.467
WILDMAN: This small box
played a key role

01:41.469 --> 01:44.069
in a spine-chilling
atomic accident

01:44.071 --> 01:46.605
that played out in the skies
above the United States.

01:47.641 --> 01:51.376
The artifact is tied
to a midair disaster

01:51.378 --> 01:54.178
that nearly led to
nuclear devastation.

01:54.180 --> 01:59.084
♪♪

01:59.086 --> 02:01.520
WILDMAN:
It's the early 1960s.

02:01.522 --> 02:03.989
The world's
two greatest superpowers,

02:03.991 --> 02:06.158
the United States
and the Soviet Union,

02:06.160 --> 02:10.162
are locked in a titanic
struggle for global supremacy,

02:10.164 --> 02:13.198
with each side seeking to amass
more nuclear weapons

02:13.200 --> 02:15.233
than the other.

02:15.235 --> 02:18.070
Tensions are so high
that the U.S. Air Force

02:18.072 --> 02:19.738
keeps almost 30%

02:19.740 --> 02:22.207
of its long-range
nuclear bombers airborne

02:22.209 --> 02:24.576
and ready to strike
at all times.

02:26.980 --> 02:31.750
On January 23rd, 1961,
one of those bombers,

02:31.752 --> 02:34.085
a B-52 Stratofortress,

02:34.087 --> 02:36.555
takes off from
Seymour Johnson Air Force Base

02:36.557 --> 02:39.290
in Goldsboro, North Carolina.

02:39.292 --> 02:42.027
On board are eight crew members

02:42.029 --> 02:45.964
and two MK 39
thermonuclear bombs.

02:45.966 --> 02:51.136
Each bomb had about 260 times
the firepower

02:51.138 --> 02:55.374
of the atomic bomb
that was dropped on Hiroshima.

02:57.410 --> 03:00.511
WILDMAN:
In command of the flight
is Major Walter Tulloch.

03:00.513 --> 03:03.649
BAILEY:
Tulloch was an ace pilot.

03:03.651 --> 03:06.685
He knew how to handle
his aircraft and his crew.

03:06.687 --> 03:08.720
He was very well-respected.

03:08.722 --> 03:11.556
♪♪

03:11.558 --> 03:13.858
WILDMAN: Tulloch's orders
are to remain on standby

03:13.860 --> 03:15.594
while circling
over the Atlantic.

03:17.297 --> 03:19.264
For the first 12 hours
of the mission,

03:19.266 --> 03:20.866
everything goes smoothly.

03:23.137 --> 03:24.669
But then, while the bomber

03:24.671 --> 03:27.139
is over the coast
of North Carolina,

03:27.141 --> 03:31.476
the pilot notices that there is
a tear in the plane's right wing

03:31.478 --> 03:33.612
and the jet fuel is leaking out.

03:33.614 --> 03:36.414
♪♪

03:36.416 --> 03:40.619
Tulloch immediately radios
Seymour Johnson Air Force Base.

03:40.621 --> 03:43.621
They advised that
he come back to base.

03:43.623 --> 03:46.992
They would take care
of this mechanical repair.

03:46.994 --> 03:49.094
WILDMAN: So the commander
turns the plane around

03:49.096 --> 03:52.764
and begins to descend
towards the airfield.

03:52.766 --> 03:56.602
But just as the craft
reaches 10,000 feet,

03:56.604 --> 03:58.837
the unthinkable happens.

03:59.773 --> 04:03.842
A massive explosion blows
the right wing completely off.

04:05.012 --> 04:07.078
BAILEY:
It was pure chaos.

04:07.080 --> 04:08.947
This was a pilot's
worst nightmare.

04:10.183 --> 04:13.018
WILDMAN: The plane plummets
towards the ground.

04:13.020 --> 04:15.787
If the aircraft's
two bombs detonate,

04:15.789 --> 04:18.856
the results will be
catastrophic.

04:18.858 --> 04:21.793
BAILEY:
Anyone within a 20-mile radius

04:21.795 --> 04:25.030
would be instantly
and dramatically killed.

04:25.032 --> 04:27.599
This was going to be
the deadliest accident

04:27.601 --> 04:29.401
in American history.

04:31.739 --> 04:34.472
WILDMAN: Major Walter Tulloch
and his crew have no choice

04:34.474 --> 04:36.341
but to bail out.

04:36.343 --> 04:39.177
Moments later,
the nuclear-armed aircraft

04:39.179 --> 04:41.112
slams into a tobacco field.

04:41.114 --> 04:44.082
♪♪

04:44.084 --> 04:47.886
As he descends in his parachute,
Tulloch fears the worst.

04:47.888 --> 04:49.888
BAILEY:
Tulloch squeezed his eyes shut.

04:49.890 --> 04:52.891
He waited, he waited,

04:52.893 --> 04:55.193
and then he realized
that nothing happened.

04:55.195 --> 04:58.630
Miraculously,
the bombs did not go off.

05:00.433 --> 05:04.169
WILDMAN:
Tulloch and four members
of the crew land safely.

05:04.171 --> 05:06.905
Tragically, three of the airmen
do not survive.

05:09.242 --> 05:11.576
Hours later,
Air Force investigators

05:11.578 --> 05:14.112
find one of the bombs
lodged in the ground,

05:14.114 --> 05:16.982
having failed to explode.

05:16.984 --> 05:19.918
They find the second weapon
stuck in a tree,

05:19.920 --> 05:21.719
dangling from its parachute.

05:21.721 --> 05:24.189
♪♪

05:24.191 --> 05:26.858
So why didn't
these bombs explode?

05:26.860 --> 05:29.994
The answer lies in
a six-step arming sequence

05:29.996 --> 05:33.264
that acted as a failsafe
on each weapon.

05:33.266 --> 05:35.233
For the one landed
in the ground,

05:35.235 --> 05:37.869
the sequence
had not been initiated.

05:37.871 --> 05:40.172
But for the device
found hanging in the tree,

05:40.174 --> 05:41.807
it was a very different story.

05:43.477 --> 05:47.479
In fact, this bomb had come
perilously close to going off.

05:48.482 --> 05:51.349
Of the six steps needed
for detonation,

05:51.351 --> 05:53.284
five had been achieved.

05:54.421 --> 05:56.687
WILDMAN: All that prevented
the bomb from detonating

05:56.689 --> 06:00.291
was one simple,
hand-controlled on/off switch.

06:01.294 --> 06:05.530
It was literally one step away
from nuclear catastrophe.

06:05.532 --> 06:09.701
♪♪

06:09.703 --> 06:12.504
WILDMAN: In the aftermath,
the U.S. military revises

06:12.506 --> 06:16.674
the arming mechanisms for the
weapons in its nuclear arsenal.

06:16.676 --> 06:19.844
Instead of using simple
switches, they create a system

06:19.846 --> 06:24.015
that requires a complex series
of digital codes.

06:24.017 --> 06:28.253
It's called the
Permissive Action Link, or PAL.

06:28.255 --> 06:32.524
BAILEY:
It was made to be only armed
by an authorized user.

06:32.526 --> 06:36.594
This essentially ushered in
the era of the nuclear codes

06:36.596 --> 06:38.764
that we know and have today.

06:40.967 --> 06:43.000
WILDMAN:
Today, one of the very first

06:43.002 --> 06:45.870
Permissive Action Link devices
is on display

06:45.872 --> 06:48.940
at the National Museum of
Nuclear Science & History

06:48.942 --> 06:51.109
in Albuquerque, New Mexico.

06:51.111 --> 06:53.612
It recalls
the terrifying accident

06:53.614 --> 06:55.146
that left the United States

06:55.148 --> 06:58.283
one switch away
from nuclear annihilation.

06:58.285 --> 07:02.621
♪♪

07:02.623 --> 07:05.056
North Dakota is home
to the majestic

07:05.058 --> 07:08.159
Theodore Roosevelt
National Park.

07:08.161 --> 07:10.962
Named in honor
of the nation's 26th president

07:10.964 --> 07:13.331
who owned a cattle ranch here,

07:13.333 --> 07:16.968
this sprawling preserve
features stalwart buttes,

07:16.970 --> 07:20.338
soaring pinnacles,
and jagged canyons.

07:20.340 --> 07:23.708
♪♪

07:23.710 --> 07:26.711
And inside the Visitor Center
is a collection of items

07:26.713 --> 07:30.248
related to Roosevelt's days
on the frontier,

07:30.250 --> 07:33.919
including horns from the cattle
raised from his property,

07:33.921 --> 07:37.555
a book based on
his popular nickname, "Teddy,"

07:37.557 --> 07:39.357
and the shirt he wore
while delivering

07:39.359 --> 07:41.860
a campaign speech in 1912.

07:41.862 --> 07:45.530
♪♪

07:45.532 --> 07:49.467
But one rugged accessory has
an incredible story to tell.

07:49.469 --> 07:51.469
PORGES: The artifact
is made of dark leather

07:51.471 --> 07:54.538
and has some soft
bear fur on it.

07:54.540 --> 07:56.741
It's about 40 inches long,

07:56.743 --> 07:59.077
and it has a shiny metal buckle.

08:01.581 --> 08:04.749
WILDMAN:
This belt bore witness
to a deadly confrontation

08:04.751 --> 08:07.318
with a ruthless
band of outlaws.

08:07.320 --> 08:10.488
PORGES:
This is rollicking tale
of frontier justice

08:10.490 --> 08:11.623
in the Old West.

08:11.625 --> 08:15.426
♪♪

08:15.428 --> 08:18.463
WILDMAN:
It's 1884 -- New York.

08:18.465 --> 08:21.233
After the sudden deaths
of his wife and mother,

08:21.235 --> 08:24.035
27-year-old politician
Theodore Roosevelt

08:24.037 --> 08:25.770
is stricken with grief.

08:25.772 --> 08:30.442
His wife and mother both died
on the exact same date --

08:30.444 --> 08:31.843
Valentine's Day.

08:31.845 --> 08:34.112
Roosevelt needed
a place to grieve.

08:34.114 --> 08:35.881
He needed to get far away.

08:37.917 --> 08:40.452
WILDMAN: Roosevelt --
long an outdoor lover --

08:40.454 --> 08:43.621
moves to the Dakota Territory
and purchases a ranch.

08:44.391 --> 08:46.658
For the next two years,
he throws himself

08:46.660 --> 08:49.260
into this new active lifestyle.

08:49.262 --> 08:51.262
He tended cattle, he hunted,

08:51.264 --> 08:53.364
he even served
as a deputy sheriff.

08:54.434 --> 08:57.636
WILDMAN:
But his tranquil life is about
to be rudely interrupted.

08:59.873 --> 09:02.073
In March 1886,

09:02.075 --> 09:05.477
Roosevelt is preparing to cross
a stream on his property

09:05.479 --> 09:08.780
when he discovers
his boat is missing.

09:08.782 --> 09:12.150
He finds the ropes
used to tie the craft to a tree

09:12.152 --> 09:13.351
have been cut.

09:13.353 --> 09:16.488
The evidence leaves him
with little doubt.

09:16.490 --> 09:18.690
His boat has been stolen.

09:18.692 --> 09:22.027
Roosevelt was in no mood
to abide by such a petty theft.

09:23.229 --> 09:26.364
WILDMAN:
He learns from other ranchers
that a group of three thieves

09:26.366 --> 09:30.035
have been stealing
cattle and horses for years.

09:30.037 --> 09:31.970
The outlaws are believed
to be holed up

09:31.972 --> 09:35.673
in a tiny shack
20 miles downstream.

09:35.675 --> 09:38.843
Roosevelt resolves to
put to an end to their crimes.

09:38.845 --> 09:41.646
If Roosevelt didn't put a stop
to this thievery,

09:41.648 --> 09:43.715
it was going to happen again,

09:43.717 --> 09:45.917
and again, and again.

09:47.053 --> 09:49.220
WILDMAN: So he recruits
two of his ranch hands

09:49.222 --> 09:51.322
to help him
track down the criminals

09:51.324 --> 09:52.891
and take them into custody.

09:54.394 --> 09:58.596
The small posse gathers
weapons and supplies,

09:58.598 --> 10:01.466
including this ammo belt,
now on display

10:01.468 --> 10:04.936
at the Theodore Roosevelt
National Park Visitor Center,

10:04.938 --> 10:06.804
and heads into the wilderness.

10:06.806 --> 10:09.607
♪♪

10:09.609 --> 10:12.810
Three days later,
the trio comes upon a cabin.

10:12.812 --> 10:15.747
Tied up in front
is Roosevelt's boat.

10:15.749 --> 10:20.151
There it was, moored directly
in front of the bandits' cabin.

10:20.153 --> 10:22.320
They knew they had their men.

10:24.557 --> 10:26.157
[ Gun cocks ]

10:26.159 --> 10:29.094
WILDMAN:
Roosevelt and his ranch hands
sneak towards the cabin

10:29.096 --> 10:31.429
and take one bandit by surprise.

10:31.431 --> 10:33.898
Roosevelt doesn't want to
go in guns a-blazing.

10:33.900 --> 10:35.833
He wants to capture
these men alive

10:35.835 --> 10:37.736
and try them for their crimes.

10:38.938 --> 10:41.072
WILDMAN: Moments later,
they spot the other two

10:41.074 --> 10:43.174
returning to the cabin,

10:43.176 --> 10:45.610
and encircle
the unsuspecting bandits.

10:46.847 --> 10:49.781
Roosevelt orders the robbers
to drop their weapons.

10:51.918 --> 10:53.184
PORGES:
It was a standoff.

10:53.186 --> 10:56.121
Everybody had their weapons
pointed at each other,

10:56.123 --> 10:57.922
and no man was safe.

10:59.259 --> 11:02.994
BAILEY: So who will win this
high-stakes frontier showdown?

11:08.101 --> 11:10.167
It's 1886.

11:10.169 --> 11:13.471
At a remote cabin in the heart
of the Dakota Territory

11:13.473 --> 11:16.107
a deadly standoff is underway.

11:16.109 --> 11:19.144
On one side
is a violent gang of thieves,

11:19.146 --> 11:22.379
on the other, a posse
of law-abiding citizens

11:22.381 --> 11:25.783
led by none other
than Theodore Roosevelt.

11:25.785 --> 11:28.319
So who will win
this epic showdown?

11:28.321 --> 11:31.723
♪♪

11:31.725 --> 11:33.691
Theodore Roosevelt
orders the thieves

11:33.693 --> 11:35.160
to lower their guns...

11:37.430 --> 11:42.267
...and after several
tense moments, they comply.

11:42.269 --> 11:43.801
PORGES:
The bandits were outnumbered,

11:43.803 --> 11:46.204
and they knew this was<i> not</i>
going to end well for them,

11:46.206 --> 11:47.738
so they dropped their weapons...

11:47.740 --> 11:50.207
♪♪

11:50.209 --> 11:52.610
...and they surrendered.

11:52.612 --> 11:54.979
WILDMAN: Roosevelt takes
the villains into custody,

11:54.981 --> 11:57.515
while his men retrieve his boat.

11:57.517 --> 12:01.252
He then brings the robbers to
the sheriff in the nearest town.

12:01.254 --> 12:04.355
There, the criminal gang
is convicted of theft,

12:04.357 --> 12:06.658
and sentenced to
two years hard labor.

12:06.660 --> 12:09.160
♪♪

12:09.162 --> 12:11.562
But the story doesn't end there.

12:11.564 --> 12:14.098
This tale of how he captured
these thieves

12:14.100 --> 12:15.900
and delivered them to justice --

12:15.902 --> 12:18.503
it spreads far,
and it spreads fast.

12:18.505 --> 12:21.473
♪♪

12:21.475 --> 12:24.175
WILDMAN:
Roosevelt becomes known
for his strong resolve

12:24.177 --> 12:27.245
against corruption
and injustice.

12:27.247 --> 12:30.581
He returns to New York,
where in 1894

12:30.583 --> 12:34.084
he's elected commissioner
of the New York City Police.

12:34.086 --> 12:37.489
He later serves
as the state governor.

12:37.491 --> 12:41.459
In 1901, he rises to
the highest office in the land

12:41.461 --> 12:43.862
as the nation's 26th president.

12:43.864 --> 12:49.334
♪♪

12:49.336 --> 12:52.136
Today, this ammunition belt
worn by Roosevelt

12:52.138 --> 12:54.672
during his pursuit
of the Badlands bandits

12:54.674 --> 12:57.809
is on display at the
Theodore Roosevelt National Park

12:57.811 --> 13:00.145
in North Dakota.

13:00.147 --> 13:02.614
It recalls the adventure-loving
president

13:02.616 --> 13:05.482
who laid down the law
in the Wild West.

13:05.484 --> 13:10.421
♪♪

13:10.423 --> 13:12.490
Los Angeles, California,
is known

13:12.492 --> 13:15.226
as the movie capital
of the world,

13:15.228 --> 13:19.563
but it also offers an array
of other cultural pursuits.

13:19.565 --> 13:22.833
The city boasts
over 300 museums --

13:22.835 --> 13:26.004
more than any other
metropolis in the country.

13:26.006 --> 13:30.241
And among them is perhaps
L.A.'s most stylish --

13:30.243 --> 13:33.711
The Fashion Institute of Design
& Merchandising Museum.

13:33.713 --> 13:37.115
♪♪

13:37.117 --> 13:41.519
The collection boasts a stunning
array of haute couture,

13:41.521 --> 13:43.654
including an elegant
evening coat

13:43.656 --> 13:46.757
inspired by Persian tile work,

13:46.759 --> 13:51.362
a silk presentation dress worn
by a Dallas debutante in 1928...

13:52.866 --> 13:56.033
...and a gilded clutch
designed by Alexander McQueen.

13:56.035 --> 13:59.337
♪♪

13:59.339 --> 14:01.639
But among these flawless pieces

14:01.641 --> 14:04.942
is one item with
a harrowing story to tell.

14:04.944 --> 14:08.479
The artifact is made of
delicate, cream-colored silk.

14:08.481 --> 14:10.848
It's about 48 inches long.

14:10.850 --> 14:13.318
There are flowers made
of green and white fabric.

14:14.754 --> 14:18.323
It was worn by one of
Hollywood's first bombshells.

14:18.325 --> 14:21.459
♪♪

14:21.461 --> 14:24.429
WILDMAN: This gown
recalls a shocking crime

14:24.431 --> 14:27.031
that shook Tinseltown
to its core.

14:27.033 --> 14:29.467
This is a story
of a mysterious death

14:29.469 --> 14:31.769
during the Golden Age
of Hollywood.

14:31.771 --> 14:36.374
♪♪

14:36.376 --> 14:40.712
WILDMAN:
It's September 5th, 1932 --
Los Angeles, California.

14:41.781 --> 14:43.214
Police have just been called

14:43.216 --> 14:46.384
to an elegant mansion
in Beverly Hills.

14:46.386 --> 14:49.320
When they arrive, they are met
by a shocking sight.

14:50.523 --> 14:53.524
In the master bedroom,
lying naked on the floor,

14:53.526 --> 14:56.260
is the dead body of a man.

14:56.262 --> 14:59.497
He has a bullet wound
to the side of his head,

14:59.499 --> 15:03.968
and in his hand is
a .38 caliber revolver.

15:03.970 --> 15:07.272
According to the maid, the man
is the owner of the house,

15:07.274 --> 15:10.275
42-year-old movie producer
Paul Bern.

15:12.112 --> 15:16.280
Paul Bern was one of the most
successful producers at MGM,

15:16.282 --> 15:19.784
which was the most successful
studio at that time.

15:19.786 --> 15:23.387
Anything that his name was on
was a guaranteed hit.

15:23.389 --> 15:26.290
WILDMAN:
Based on the physical evidence
at the crime scene,

15:26.292 --> 15:28.826
authorities conclude
that Bern shot himself.

15:29.862 --> 15:32.296
It was kind of
a textbook suicide.

15:32.298 --> 15:34.998
♪♪

15:35.000 --> 15:38.903
WILDMAN:
News of Paul Bern's suicide
shocks the city,

15:38.905 --> 15:42.306
but in the aftermath,
one question remains --

15:42.308 --> 15:44.175
why did he do it?

15:46.046 --> 15:48.513
Bern seemed to have
a flourishing career,

15:48.515 --> 15:51.582
and was happily married
to the biggest star of the era,

15:51.584 --> 15:53.450
actress Jean Harlow.

15:53.452 --> 15:56.787
At 22 years old,
she was Hollywood's golden girl,

15:56.789 --> 15:58.723
she was the first bombshell,

15:58.725 --> 16:02.794
and this was one of the first
power-couple marriages

16:02.796 --> 16:03.828
in Hollywood.

16:03.830 --> 16:07.498
♪♪

16:07.500 --> 16:10.267
WILDMAN:
But then a detail emerges
that suggests that

16:10.269 --> 16:13.337
there might be more to
this tragedy than meets the eye.

16:14.541 --> 16:17.074
Bern's butler reveals
that he found the body

16:17.076 --> 16:19.843
around 11:45 in the morning.

16:19.845 --> 16:24.415
He immediately called
Bern's boss at MGM,

16:24.417 --> 16:26.484
but the police weren't
actually notified

16:26.486 --> 16:29.153
for another 2 1/2 hours.

16:29.155 --> 16:30.488
DENNIS:
This was more than enough time

16:30.490 --> 16:32.757
for someone to mess with
the crime scene.

16:32.759 --> 16:35.493
It may have been a murder.

16:35.495 --> 16:39.664
WILDMAN:
So what's the sinister truth
behind this Tinseltown tragedy?

16:44.103 --> 16:46.871
It's 1932 -- Hollywood.

16:46.873 --> 16:49.440
Movie producer Paul Bern
was found dead

16:49.442 --> 16:51.509
in his Beverly Hills mansion.

16:51.511 --> 16:55.212
Initially, it looked as if
his death was a suicide,

16:55.214 --> 16:58.549
but as more details emerge,
it becomes increasingly clear

16:58.551 --> 17:01.686
that Bern may have been
the victim of foul play.

17:01.688 --> 17:05.556
So what's the truth behind
this Tinseltown tragedy?

17:05.558 --> 17:08.492
♪♪

17:08.494 --> 17:13.498
1986 -- nearly 60 years
after the producer's demise,

17:13.500 --> 17:17.101
a crime writer named
Samuel Marx takes up the case.

17:17.103 --> 17:20.371
DENNIS:
Marx was a screenwriter
once upon a time,

17:20.373 --> 17:22.907
but he was also
a close friend of Bern's.

17:22.909 --> 17:25.242
He felt that there was
more to the story

17:25.244 --> 17:28.145
than what he had
been led to believe.

17:28.147 --> 17:31.616
WILDMAN: First Marx focuses
on the person closest to Bern...

17:33.252 --> 17:35.753
...his wife, Jean Harlow,

17:35.755 --> 17:38.055
but the records show
that detectives on the case

17:38.057 --> 17:41.091
believed the actress
had an airtight alibi.

17:41.093 --> 17:43.560
Harlow had been working
all weekend on a movie --

17:43.562 --> 17:46.697
a movie called "Red Dust"
costarring Clark Gable.

17:46.699 --> 17:49.900
♪♪

17:49.902 --> 17:51.436
WILDMAN:
Marx then sifts through

17:51.438 --> 17:53.304
contemporaneous
newspaper accounts

17:53.306 --> 17:56.507
of Bern's death from 1932.

17:56.509 --> 17:57.975
Finally, he unearths

17:57.977 --> 18:00.444
an intriguing snippet
of information.

18:00.446 --> 18:03.280
♪♪

18:03.282 --> 18:06.383
Before Bern moved
to Hollywood in the 1920s,

18:06.385 --> 18:08.252
he had an acrimonious breakup

18:08.254 --> 18:12.056
with a woman in New York
named Dorothy Millette.

18:12.058 --> 18:15.259
DENNIS:
Dorothy was a failed actress

18:15.261 --> 18:18.662
and was probably quite jealous
of his new relationship.

18:18.664 --> 18:20.397
WILDMAN:
And that's not all.

18:20.399 --> 18:22.633
Two days after
Bern's body was found,

18:22.635 --> 18:25.135
Millette herself
was found dead,

18:25.137 --> 18:27.905
having killed herself
in California.

18:27.907 --> 18:30.341
DENNIS: Marx believed,
in a jealous rage,

18:30.343 --> 18:32.743
Dorothy traveled
from New York to Hollywood

18:32.745 --> 18:36.080
just to confront Paul Bern,

18:36.082 --> 18:39.950
and, in all likelihood,
murdered Paul Bern.

18:39.952 --> 18:41.886
WILDMAN:
Having killed her former lover,

18:41.888 --> 18:43.955
Millette then killed herself.

18:45.024 --> 18:48.025
Then, one final clue
reveals the truth

18:48.027 --> 18:50.361
of what may have happened
that night.

18:51.831 --> 18:53.831
Marx discovers
an old interview

18:53.833 --> 18:58.669
given by a former MGM employee
named Howard Strickling.

18:58.671 --> 19:00.905
Strickling says
that in the 1930s,

19:00.907 --> 19:04.775
he was employed by
the movie studio as a fixer.

19:04.777 --> 19:06.910
DENNIS: If a star
got himself in trouble,

19:06.912 --> 19:09.580
there were fixers that were
employed by the studio

19:09.582 --> 19:12.849
who were able to make sure
that the tawdry, lurid details

19:12.851 --> 19:15.586
remained out
of the mainstream press.

19:15.588 --> 19:19.389
WILDMAN:
Strickling claims that on the
day Bern's body was discovered,

19:19.391 --> 19:22.693
he was immediately
dispatched to the house.

19:22.695 --> 19:26.197
When he arrived, it was clear
from the position of the gun

19:26.199 --> 19:29.867
that the producer
had been murdered.

19:29.869 --> 19:33.203
The gun was found across
the room from Paul's body.

19:34.607 --> 19:39.343
WILDMAN:
MGM worried Harlow would be
dragged into the investigation.

19:39.345 --> 19:41.746
So, to avoid the spectacle
of their star

19:41.748 --> 19:43.381
being questioned by the police,

19:43.383 --> 19:46.951
Strickling staged the scene
to look like a suicide.

19:46.953 --> 19:50.755
MGM would not allow
its biggest star to be involved

19:50.757 --> 19:52.890
in any way
with a murder scandal.

19:52.892 --> 19:56.427
♪♪

19:56.429 --> 19:59.630
WILDMAN:
Samuel Marx publishes
his book in 1990.

19:59.632 --> 20:01.365
But despite his conclusions,

20:01.367 --> 20:05.102
what really happened that day
remains shrouded in mystery.

20:05.104 --> 20:08.172
♪♪

20:08.174 --> 20:12.443
Today, this dress, once worn
by Bern's wife, Jean Harlow,

20:12.445 --> 20:13.711
is on display at

20:13.713 --> 20:16.113
the Fashion Institute
of Design & Marketing Museum

20:16.115 --> 20:18.248
in Los Angeles.

20:18.250 --> 20:22.119
It recalls a famous actress
who was almost wrapped up

20:22.121 --> 20:24.688
in an infamous
Hollywood murder mystery.

20:24.690 --> 20:28.526
♪♪

20:28.528 --> 20:30.261
Wilmington, Delaware --

20:30.263 --> 20:34.432
this riverside city rose to
prominence during the Civil War

20:34.434 --> 20:38.135
as one of the Union's
leading suppliers of gunpowder.

20:38.137 --> 20:41.939
Today, this explosive legacy
is preserved

20:41.941 --> 20:44.408
at the Hagley Museum
and Library.

20:44.410 --> 20:47.044
♪♪

20:47.046 --> 20:50.014
Located on the grounds
of a 19th-century mill

20:50.016 --> 20:52.315
once owned
by the DuPont Company,

20:52.317 --> 20:56.220
the collection includes
antique powder kegs,

20:56.222 --> 20:58.456
vintage dynamite sticks,

20:58.458 --> 21:00.491
and even
a fully functional cannon.

21:02.294 --> 21:06.130
But amid these deadly relics
is a harmless piece of fabric.

21:06.132 --> 21:10.368
There's a pale-yellow swatch
of material behind glass.

21:10.370 --> 21:14.171
The material looks as if it's
tightly woven into a pattern

21:14.173 --> 21:16.607
with something embedded
in the center of it.

21:18.944 --> 21:22.612
WILDMAN: This artifact recalls
a resilient engineer,

21:22.614 --> 21:24.281
an ambitious experiment,

21:24.283 --> 21:26.917
and one of the world's
strongest materials.

21:26.919 --> 21:28.652
This was an amazing invention

21:28.654 --> 21:30.987
that has saved
thousands of lives.

21:30.989 --> 21:34.692
♪♪

21:34.694 --> 21:37.395
WILDMAN:
It's the 1960s.

21:37.397 --> 21:39.997
The expansion of the
Interstate Highway System

21:39.999 --> 21:43.734
has led Americans
to drive more than ever.

21:43.736 --> 21:45.202
To keep the country moving,

21:45.204 --> 21:49.073
car manufacturers have created
longer-lasting batteries,

21:49.075 --> 21:51.909
improved
automatic transmissions,

21:51.911 --> 21:54.612
and introduced
front-wheel drive.

21:54.614 --> 21:58.982
But one crucial car part
remains ripe for improvement --

21:58.984 --> 22:00.851
tires.

22:00.853 --> 22:04.522
JACKSON:
At that time, tires were
reinforced with steel wire

22:04.524 --> 22:08.159
and, while very strong,
that's also very heavy,

22:08.161 --> 22:10.428
and that burned a lot of gas.

22:12.131 --> 22:17.635
WILDMAN:
So in 1964, one woman sets out
to make tires lighter --

22:17.637 --> 22:21.505
a chemical engineer at DuPont
named Stephanie Kwolek.

22:21.507 --> 22:24.775
JACKSON:
Kwolek had been an employee
at DuPont for over a decade,

22:24.777 --> 22:27.978
and she'd been looking for
an opportunity to strike out

22:27.980 --> 22:29.747
and show her true talents.

22:31.650 --> 22:34.985
WILDMAN:
Kwolek has spent her career
working with synthetic fabrics

22:34.987 --> 22:38.155
like nylon and rayon.

22:38.157 --> 22:40.991
Now she believes
she can create a new fiber

22:40.993 --> 22:42.326
that's lighter than steel

22:42.328 --> 22:45.062
but still strong enough
to use in tires.

22:45.064 --> 22:48.832
This material could not only
skyrocket her career,

22:48.834 --> 22:52.470
but it could improve
the lives of thousands

22:52.472 --> 22:54.872
because it would increase
fuel efficiency.

22:54.874 --> 22:57.608
♪♪

22:57.610 --> 22:59.810
WILDMAN: Typically,
synthetic materials are made

22:59.812 --> 23:02.679
by dissolving a series
of specific compounds

23:02.681 --> 23:04.215
into a solution

23:04.217 --> 23:07.218
and then spinning the
resulting liquid into a fiber.

23:08.654 --> 23:10.888
To create something
that's super strong,

23:10.890 --> 23:14.224
Kwolek believes the key
is a compound used in plastics

23:14.226 --> 23:16.494
called benzene.

23:16.496 --> 23:18.896
But when she attempts
to turn it into a fiber,

23:18.898 --> 23:21.231
she hits a setback.

23:21.233 --> 23:23.768
The benzene won't dissolve.

23:24.970 --> 23:27.437
For six months,
Kwolek tweaks her mixture,

23:27.439 --> 23:29.840
trying to create
something that will work.

23:29.842 --> 23:34.311
JACKSON:
She decided to take everything
methodically, step by step,

23:34.313 --> 23:36.714
until she'd come up
with a formula

23:36.716 --> 23:38.482
that she wanted to try out.

23:38.484 --> 23:43.954
WILDMAN:
Finally, in 1965, the determined
scientist has a breakthrough.

23:43.956 --> 23:46.390
She discovers
a unique chemical cocktail

23:46.392 --> 23:48.826
that should break down
the benzene.

23:48.828 --> 23:50.594
But when she mixes
the ingredients,

23:50.596 --> 23:53.530
the results are unlike
anything she's seen before.

23:53.532 --> 23:56.000
♪♪

23:56.002 --> 23:59.603
She expects to create a liquid
that is clear and viscous.

23:59.605 --> 24:01.672
But her experiment
has produced a thin,

24:01.674 --> 24:03.273
yellowish solution.

24:03.275 --> 24:05.409
It was runny and it was cloudy

24:05.411 --> 24:08.412
and it was nothing like
it should've been.

24:08.414 --> 24:09.713
She was stumped.

24:11.884 --> 24:15.619
WILDMAN:
Kwolek assumes her experiment
is a total failure,

24:15.621 --> 24:18.221
but she's actually
stumbled upon a solution

24:18.223 --> 24:21.625
that will find a life far
beyond the automotive world.

24:21.627 --> 24:23.861
So what is Kwolek's
incredible invention?

24:30.036 --> 24:33.971
It's 1965
in Wilmington, Delaware.

24:33.973 --> 24:36.240
Chemical engineer
Stephanie Kwolek

24:36.242 --> 24:37.708
is working on a project

24:37.710 --> 24:40.511
to develop
a lightweight car tire,

24:40.513 --> 24:42.646
but so far,
all she's been able to produce

24:42.648 --> 24:44.915
is a strange, watery substance

24:44.917 --> 24:47.918
that appears to be
practically useless.

24:47.920 --> 24:51.055
But little does she know,
she's created a material

24:51.057 --> 24:52.789
that will change the world.

24:52.791 --> 24:55.592
♪♪

24:55.594 --> 24:57.528
To determine if something
went wrong,

24:57.530 --> 24:59.663
Kwolek reexamines her work,

24:59.665 --> 25:02.132
and when she double checks
her calculations,

25:02.134 --> 25:06.136
she becomes convinced that the
fluid<i> can</i> be spun into a thread.

25:06.138 --> 25:09.340
♪♪

25:09.342 --> 25:11.809
Kwolek runs her solution
through a device

25:11.811 --> 25:15.346
that spins chemical solutions
into thin strands.

25:15.348 --> 25:17.881
It's pushed through an extruder,
kind of like spaghetti,

25:17.883 --> 25:20.884
and then you can twist those
and turn those into a fabric.

25:20.886 --> 25:24.588
♪♪

25:24.590 --> 25:27.958
WILDMAN: The machine produces
a thin, yellowish material.

25:27.960 --> 25:29.894
That came out beautifully.

25:29.896 --> 25:33.897
WILDMAN:
The thread is even stronger
than what she set out to create.

25:33.899 --> 25:37.567
Kwolek then puts the material
through a battery of tests.

25:37.569 --> 25:40.104
And what she finds
is extraordinary.

25:42.408 --> 25:43.707
JACKSON:
She tried cutting it,

25:43.709 --> 25:46.377
and the blades just glanced
right off her thread.

25:46.379 --> 25:50.447
She set the fabric on fire.
It resisted catching.

25:50.449 --> 25:52.483
WILDMAN:
But its most amazing quality

25:52.485 --> 25:55.786
is revealed
in an explosive test.

25:55.788 --> 25:58.722
JACKSON:
They shot a .38 caliber bullet

25:58.724 --> 26:02.092
at point-blank range
into the fabric,

26:02.094 --> 26:03.727
and it stopped it.

26:05.932 --> 26:09.733
WILDMAN:
Kwolek presents her new material
to her supervisors.

26:09.735 --> 26:12.469
They immediately
recognize its potential.

26:12.471 --> 26:16.340
The prospect of something
lightweight and malleable,

26:16.342 --> 26:19.309
like a fabric,
stopping a bullet

26:19.311 --> 26:20.677
is just mind-boggling.

26:20.679 --> 26:24.214
♪♪

26:24.216 --> 26:27.084
WILDMAN:
DuPont begins manufacturing
Kwolek's invention

26:27.086 --> 26:29.420
and names it Kevlar.

26:29.422 --> 26:31.555
Eventually,
the revolutionary material

26:31.557 --> 26:34.691
is used in more than
200 applications.

26:34.693 --> 26:36.493
They used it in construction,

26:36.495 --> 26:38.729
they used it
in sports equipment,

26:38.731 --> 26:40.831
they even did end up
using it in tires

26:40.833 --> 26:42.466
and it did make them lighter.

26:42.468 --> 26:44.768
But what it was
ultimately known for

26:44.770 --> 26:47.004
is being used
as bulletproof vests.

26:47.006 --> 26:50.040
♪♪

26:50.042 --> 26:52.976
WILDMAN:
Stephanie Kwolek continues
her work at DuPont,

26:52.978 --> 26:56.713
leading their research lab
until her retirement in 1989.

26:56.715 --> 26:59.316
♪♪

26:59.318 --> 27:03.420
Today, the patch of Kevlar
used in DuPont's ballistic test

27:03.422 --> 27:05.990
is on display
at the Hagley Museum and Library

27:05.992 --> 27:07.424
in Wilmington, Delaware.

27:07.426 --> 27:09.793
It recalls
an engineer's determination

27:09.795 --> 27:12.296
and her impenetrable
breakthrough.

27:12.298 --> 27:16.467
♪♪

27:16.469 --> 27:18.735
Paris, France --

27:18.737 --> 27:21.338
perched atop
this city's tallest hill

27:21.340 --> 27:24.808
is the stunning
Sacré-Coeur Basilica.

27:24.810 --> 27:29.013
Completed in 1914,
this spectacular white church

27:29.015 --> 27:31.515
was constructed to honor
the fallen soldiers

27:31.517 --> 27:34.018
of the Franco-Prussian War.

27:34.020 --> 27:36.553
And not far away
is another institution

27:36.555 --> 27:40.423
that honors the French military,
the Musée de l'Armée

27:40.425 --> 27:43.761
♪♪

27:43.763 --> 27:47.031
The collection of more
than 500,000 artifacts

27:47.033 --> 27:48.765
includes a French field cannon

27:48.767 --> 27:51.769
that saw action
during World War I,

27:51.771 --> 27:56.406
a taxi that transported troops
to the front lines in 1914,

27:56.408 --> 27:59.309
and a German mine retrieved
from the English Channel

27:59.311 --> 28:00.911
after World War II.

28:00.913 --> 28:05.649
♪♪

28:05.651 --> 28:08.618
But among these relics
of 20th-century warfare

28:08.620 --> 28:11.188
is one from a more distant era.

28:11.190 --> 28:15.793
The artifact is four feet long
and it has a six-inch hilt.

28:15.795 --> 28:21.498
It's predominantly made of steel
and has gold detailing,

28:21.500 --> 28:23.167
and it's extremely sharp.

28:23.169 --> 28:25.736
♪♪

28:25.738 --> 28:29.073
WILDMAN: This ornate weapon
recalls an epic grudge match

28:29.075 --> 28:31.308
that spanned the ages.

28:31.310 --> 28:35.045
This is the story of
the longest duel in history.

28:35.047 --> 28:39.282
♪♪

28:39.284 --> 28:41.918
WILDMAN: It's 1794.

28:41.920 --> 28:44.788
At an estate in
the French city of Strasbourg,

28:44.790 --> 28:47.591
a young Army captain
named Pierre Dupont

28:47.593 --> 28:50.160
is guarding the entrance
to an exclusive ball.

28:51.530 --> 28:54.498
At around 11:00 p.m.,
Dupont is approached

28:54.500 --> 28:58.936
by a fiery calvary man
named Francois Fournier.

28:58.938 --> 29:02.239
Fournier demands
to be let into the party,

29:02.241 --> 29:03.974
but he's not on the guest list

29:03.976 --> 29:06.710
and Dupont refuses
to grant him entry.

29:06.712 --> 29:09.045
The two of them
ended up engaging

29:09.047 --> 29:10.681
in a blistering argument.

29:10.683 --> 29:13.650
♪♪

29:13.652 --> 29:15.719
WILDMAN: Unable to resolve
their disagreement,

29:15.721 --> 29:19.990
the officers decide to settle it
as only two men of honor can.

29:21.326 --> 29:23.260
They will fight a duel.

29:23.262 --> 29:27.797
This was very much an era
when honor and chivalry

29:27.799 --> 29:30.667
and pride, really,
came before all else.

29:30.669 --> 29:34.071
♪♪

29:34.073 --> 29:36.606
WILDMAN: At the time, dueling
had long been considered

29:36.608 --> 29:39.943
a respectable way
to resolve disputes.

29:39.945 --> 29:42.412
Typically, these battles
would be fought with swords

29:42.414 --> 29:44.281
until blood was drawn.

29:44.283 --> 29:45.682
According to custom,

29:45.684 --> 29:48.485
the injured combatant
would then cede to the victor.

29:48.487 --> 29:51.021
♪♪

29:51.023 --> 29:54.958
So at the appointed hour,
Dupont and Fournier square off

29:54.960 --> 29:56.827
and draw their swords.

29:56.829 --> 29:58.762
As the combatants
begin fighting,

29:58.764 --> 30:00.664
they seem evenly matched.

30:00.666 --> 30:03.000
ALCOCK: Both of these
young French captains

30:03.002 --> 30:05.369
are incredibly skilled
swordsmen.

30:07.105 --> 30:09.706
WILDMAN:
After several furious minutes,

30:09.708 --> 30:13.043
Dupont spots an opening and
wounds the fiery Fournier.

30:13.045 --> 30:18.715
♪♪

30:18.717 --> 30:21.451
Dupont believes he's won,

30:21.453 --> 30:25.489
but his hot-tempered rival
isn't ready to admit defeat.

30:25.491 --> 30:29.359
ALCOCK:
Fournier refuses to accept
that Dupont has bettered him

30:29.361 --> 30:32.729
and he challenges Dupont
to a repeat duel.

30:32.731 --> 30:36.133
♪♪

30:36.135 --> 30:38.869
WILDMAN: One month later,
the two men face off again.

30:40.906 --> 30:41.938
Agh!

30:41.940 --> 30:43.673
Now it's Dupont
who is wounded,

30:43.675 --> 30:47.577
but this time,
<i>he</i> refuses to surrender.

30:47.579 --> 30:49.612
So they meet for a third duel...

30:49.614 --> 30:52.882
♪♪

30:52.884 --> 30:55.886
...but this match
also ends in a stalemate.

30:55.888 --> 30:59.422
Anyone else at that time might
have said to themselves,

30:59.424 --> 31:01.158
"Okay, this has gone
far enough."

31:01.160 --> 31:04.962
But neither of these men
can agree to do that.

31:04.964 --> 31:07.163
Their egos were so huge

31:07.165 --> 31:09.766
that they refused
to let the issue lie.

31:09.768 --> 31:13.036
♪♪

31:13.038 --> 31:15.505
WILDMAN:
With neither officer
willing to back down,

31:15.507 --> 31:17.074
the feud intensifies.

31:18.510 --> 31:20.310
Over the following
weeks and months,

31:20.312 --> 31:22.112
they fight a series of battles,

31:22.114 --> 31:24.581
but with each man
refusing to back down,

31:24.583 --> 31:27.050
no clear winner emerges.

31:27.052 --> 31:30.020
In fact, the stubborn soldiers
drag out their fight

31:30.022 --> 31:31.888
for 19 years.

31:32.591 --> 31:36.693
ALCOCK:
Both men received often serious
injuries during these duels,

31:36.695 --> 31:40.463
but<i> still,</i> neither one
would admit defeat.

31:40.465 --> 31:43.333
WILDMAN: So will this
grudge match ever end?

31:48.456 --> 31:51.858
WILDMAN: For almost 20 years,
two French Army officers,

31:51.860 --> 31:54.828
Pierre Dupont
and Francois Fournier,

31:54.830 --> 31:56.930
have been embroiled
over a heated dispute

31:56.932 --> 31:59.933
over a simple party invitation.

31:59.935 --> 32:03.670
But neither man is willing
to admit defeat,

32:03.672 --> 32:07.274
so who will win this
never-ending grudge match?

32:09.544 --> 32:14.081
In April 1813, Pierre Dupont
is engaged to be married

32:14.083 --> 32:17.284
and he finally decides
it's time to end his conflict

32:17.286 --> 32:20.220
with Francois Fournier
once and for all.

32:20.222 --> 32:23.690
ALCOCK:
Dupont did not believe that
it was fair on his future wife

32:23.692 --> 32:26.226
to play this game
of life and death.

32:28.530 --> 32:30.296
WILDMAN:
He reaches out to Fournier,

32:30.298 --> 32:32.899
and the two agree
to a final duel,

32:32.901 --> 32:36.836
but this contest will be
unlike their previous meetings.

32:36.838 --> 32:40.340
Since the rivals are
evenly matched with swords,

32:40.342 --> 32:42.942
this time they'll use pistols.

32:42.944 --> 32:46.112
Each officer will be armed
with just one bullet,

32:46.114 --> 32:50.717
and instead of squaring off
in an open field at 10 paces,

32:50.719 --> 32:53.754
they will fight each other
in a secluded forest.

32:53.756 --> 32:56.389
ALCOCK: Each man would start
on the opposite side

32:56.391 --> 32:58.258
of a small area of woodland

32:58.260 --> 33:00.794
and they would have to fight
their way through the trees,

33:00.796 --> 33:04.698
stalking one another much like
a wild animal stalks its prey.

33:06.901 --> 33:09.269
WILDMAN: The combatants meet
on the agreed-upon date

33:09.271 --> 33:11.471
and enter the woods.

33:11.473 --> 33:14.874
But rather than pursuing his
rival through the dense foliage,

33:14.876 --> 33:17.644
Dupont lays an ingenious trap.

33:17.646 --> 33:20.113
He uses his coat
to create a decoy

33:20.115 --> 33:22.449
by hanging the garment
on a tree.

33:22.451 --> 33:25.485
It's the oldest trick
in the book.

33:25.487 --> 33:27.888
WILDMAN: Moments later,
there's a loud gunshot.

33:29.558 --> 33:32.625
Dupont's coat
is pierced by a bullet.

33:32.627 --> 33:34.828
Fournier has taken the bait.

33:35.631 --> 33:38.998
It's then that Dupont
plays his master stroke.

33:39.000 --> 33:43.003
ALCOCK:
Dupont marched over to his enemy
and offered him a deal.

33:43.005 --> 33:44.838
He would spare Fournier's life

33:44.840 --> 33:48.608
if Fournier agreed
to accept that he had lost.

33:48.610 --> 33:50.711
WILDMAN:
Fournier reluctantly agrees,

33:50.713 --> 33:54.447
bringing the long-standing
conflict to a close.

33:54.449 --> 33:58.952
It took 19 long years for these
two men to settle the score.

33:58.954 --> 34:03.790
♪♪

34:03.792 --> 34:07.126
WILDMAN: The struggle
between Pierre Dupont
and Francois Fournier

34:07.128 --> 34:10.397
becomes known as
the longest duel in history.

34:10.399 --> 34:14.301
Over the years, the fierce
rivalry is retold in a novel.

34:14.303 --> 34:18.071
It even reaches the
silver screen in a 1977 movie,

34:18.073 --> 34:21.140
"The Duelists," helmed by
a young British director

34:21.142 --> 34:23.610
named Ridley Scott.

34:25.614 --> 34:27.948
Today, a French officer's sword

34:27.950 --> 34:31.618
like the ones used by Dupont
and Fournier in their many duels

34:31.620 --> 34:33.954
is on display at
the Musée de l'Armée

34:33.956 --> 34:35.755
in Paris, France.

34:35.757 --> 34:38.959
It's a pointed reminder
of two stubborn men

34:38.961 --> 34:40.827
who refused to back down.

34:40.829 --> 34:44.497
♪♪

34:44.499 --> 34:45.965
Houston, Texas, is home

34:45.967 --> 34:49.302
to one of the most distinctive
structures in the nation --

34:49.304 --> 34:52.772
the Shri Swaminarayan Mandir.

34:52.774 --> 34:56.843
This spectacular Hindu temple
is 73 feet tall

34:56.845 --> 35:00.113
and built out of 33,000
hand-carved blocks

35:00.115 --> 35:03.716
of Italian marble
and Turkish limestone.

35:03.718 --> 35:06.519
And not far from
this architectural wonder

35:06.521 --> 35:09.990
is another famed
cultural institution --

35:09.992 --> 35:12.292
the Museum of Fine Arts,
Houston.

35:12.294 --> 35:15.595
♪♪

35:15.597 --> 35:19.265
Among the highlights is
an ivory flask carved in India

35:19.267 --> 35:21.734
during the 1600s,

35:21.736 --> 35:23.270
a painting of water lilies

35:23.272 --> 35:26.339
created by the famous
French master Claude Monet...

35:28.209 --> 35:31.711
...and an elegant 19th-century
American side chair.

35:31.713 --> 35:35.014
♪♪

35:35.016 --> 35:38.685
But one artifact shines brighter
than the rest.

35:38.687 --> 35:40.153
It's made of gold,

35:40.155 --> 35:43.323
and it measures about
one foot in diameter.

35:43.325 --> 35:48.261
It's round with many leaves
and little flower details

35:48.263 --> 35:49.962
all the way around.

35:49.964 --> 35:53.366
♪♪

35:53.368 --> 35:55.235
WILDMAN:
This golden crown recalls

35:55.237 --> 35:58.672
the most celebrated genius
of the ancient world

35:58.674 --> 36:02.042
and the unlikely origins
of a triumphant phrase.

36:02.044 --> 36:04.577
This is the story of math...

36:04.579 --> 36:05.812
nudity...

36:05.814 --> 36:07.513
and a famous expression.

36:07.515 --> 36:14.120
♪♪

36:14.122 --> 36:18.992
WILDMAN: The story begins
in the 3rd century BC in Greece.

36:18.994 --> 36:21.127
The city of Syracuse
is experiencing

36:21.129 --> 36:25.065
an unprecedented period
of peace and prosperity.

36:25.067 --> 36:27.267
According to legend,
the city's ruler,

36:27.269 --> 36:29.069
a man named Hiero,

36:29.071 --> 36:31.170
wishes to make an offering
to the gods

36:31.172 --> 36:33.406
of an extravagant golden crown.

36:35.543 --> 36:38.478
Hiero gives a bar of pure gold
to a goldsmith

36:38.480 --> 36:41.081
and instructs him to use
every single ounce of it

36:41.083 --> 36:43.082
to create an elaborate crown.

36:43.084 --> 36:45.819
♪♪

36:45.821 --> 36:47.853
Later,
when the goldsmith delivers

36:47.855 --> 36:49.356
the completed headpiece,

36:49.358 --> 36:52.359
it surpasses
the king's expectations.

36:52.361 --> 36:53.960
HANNIGAN:
This is no ordinary crown.

36:53.962 --> 36:56.963
In fact, it resembles
a laurel wreath

36:56.965 --> 36:58.898
and it's astounding --

36:58.900 --> 37:02.402
beautiful, intricate,
well-crafted.

37:03.638 --> 37:07.507
WILDMAN: But as time passes,
Hiero hears a troubling rumor.

37:07.509 --> 37:10.443
There are whispers that
the ruler has been swindled.

37:12.047 --> 37:14.314
It's said that
the goldsmith pocketed

37:14.316 --> 37:17.216
some of the precious metal
and covered his tracks

37:17.218 --> 37:20.854
by replacing it with silver
in the finished crown.

37:20.856 --> 37:23.723
The amount would be so small
that no one would notice,

37:23.725 --> 37:27.327
but more than enough
to enrich the goldsmith.

37:27.329 --> 37:29.929
Hiero is furious.

37:29.931 --> 37:33.867
The idea of being cheated
by one of this loyal subjects

37:33.869 --> 37:35.735
incensed the king.

37:35.737 --> 37:38.804
WILDMAN: The ruler resolves
to learn the truth,

37:38.806 --> 37:43.109
so Hiero calls upon the
wisest person in his kingdom --

37:43.111 --> 37:45.878
a man named Archimedes.

37:45.880 --> 37:48.748
HANNIGAN: Archimedes was
the most famous mathematician

37:48.750 --> 37:50.784
and inventor in ancient Greece.

37:50.786 --> 37:54.120
And he was well-known
as a genius.

37:54.122 --> 37:57.223
WILDMAN:
Archimedes, the famous inventor
of the pulley system

37:57.225 --> 37:58.858
and the water pump,

37:58.860 --> 38:01.995
takes the headpiece to
his workshop for examination.

38:01.997 --> 38:04.998
♪♪

38:05.000 --> 38:07.901
The mathematician weighs
the crown against a gold bar

38:07.903 --> 38:09.302
that is identical to the one

38:09.304 --> 38:11.838
originally given
to the goldsmith.

38:11.840 --> 38:15.775
They weigh the same,
but this doesn't prove anything.

38:15.777 --> 38:18.845
The nefarious artisan
could have stolen a bit of gold

38:18.847 --> 38:21.781
and then replaced it with
an equal weight of silver.

38:21.783 --> 38:25.017
Archimedes is not satisfied
with this simple measurement

38:25.019 --> 38:27.921
and he intends to investigate
the matter further.

38:29.257 --> 38:31.123
WILDMAN: He considers
melting down the crown

38:31.125 --> 38:33.159
and checking its purity
that way,

38:33.161 --> 38:35.929
but he would have to destroy
the crown in the process.

38:35.931 --> 38:37.597
HANNIGAN:
He can't damage it in any way

38:37.599 --> 38:39.499
because as
an offering to the gods,

38:39.501 --> 38:42.869
that would be disrespectful
and possibly blasphemous.

38:42.871 --> 38:46.539
WILDMAN: So how can Archimedes
crack this golden riddle?

38:54.315 --> 38:58.117
It's the 3rd century BC
in the Greek city of Syracuse.

38:58.119 --> 38:59.619
Mathematician Archimedes

38:59.621 --> 39:02.388
has been asked
to solve a puzzling conundrum --

39:02.390 --> 39:04.323
how to determine
if a royal crown

39:04.325 --> 39:06.759
is made of pure gold.

39:06.761 --> 39:08.027
The answer will lead to

39:08.029 --> 39:10.763
one of the splashiest
scientific discoveries

39:10.765 --> 39:13.500
and famous phrases of all time.

39:13.502 --> 39:16.736
♪♪

39:16.738 --> 39:21.040
To clear his mind, Archimedes
visits the local bathhouse.

39:21.042 --> 39:24.911
He fills a tub to the brim
and steps in.

39:24.913 --> 39:27.647
As he lowers himself
into the hot water,

39:27.649 --> 39:30.550
he notices that some of it
spills over the side.

39:32.353 --> 39:35.422
It's then that he makes
a revolutionary observation.

39:36.958 --> 39:39.859
The volume of the water
that spilled out of the bath

39:39.861 --> 39:42.462
was equal to the volume
of Archimedes' body.

39:43.899 --> 39:46.365
WILDMAN: In an instant,
the mathematician in struck

39:46.367 --> 39:47.934
with a solution to the problem.

39:49.103 --> 39:52.238
Archimedes knows that gold
is denser than silver.

39:52.240 --> 39:54.774
That means that
if he takes a piece of gold

39:54.776 --> 39:57.710
and a piece of silver
that are the exact same weight,

39:57.712 --> 40:00.113
the piece of gold
will be smaller.

40:00.115 --> 40:03.550
This is the key
to unlocking the mystery.

40:03.552 --> 40:07.053
Archimedes reasoned that if
the crown was pure gold,

40:07.055 --> 40:09.923
it would displace
an equal amount of water

40:09.925 --> 40:14.127
as the golden bar identical to
the one given to the goldsmith.

40:14.863 --> 40:17.263
WILDMAN: But if it's made
out of gold<i> and</i> silver,

40:17.265 --> 40:19.399
it will displace more water.

40:21.870 --> 40:24.838
Filled with excitement,
Archimedes leaps out of the bath

40:24.840 --> 40:28.607
and utters an exclamation
that will echo down the ages.

40:28.609 --> 40:29.809
Eureka! Eureka!

40:29.811 --> 40:32.879
He ran out of the bathhouse,
naked,

40:32.881 --> 40:35.648
screaming,
"Eureka! Eureka!"

40:35.650 --> 40:39.819
The expression is just Greek
for, "I have found it."

40:41.890 --> 40:45.291
WILDMAN:
After putting his robe back on,
Archimedes tests the crown.

40:46.227 --> 40:49.094
First, he fills a bucket
to the brim with water,

40:49.096 --> 40:51.331
drops the gold bar in,

40:51.333 --> 40:55.101
and then measures the amount
of water that spills out.

40:55.103 --> 40:58.705
Then, Archimedes refills the
bucket and lowers in the crown.

40:59.507 --> 41:01.107
To everyone's surprise,

41:01.109 --> 41:03.976
even more water
splashes over the side.

41:03.978 --> 41:08.648
This means the crown takes up
more space than the gold bar.

41:08.650 --> 41:12.117
♪♪

41:12.119 --> 41:14.654
WILDMAN: It confirms
Hiero's suspicions.

41:14.656 --> 41:18.191
The gold crown has been mixed
with another metal.

41:18.193 --> 41:20.126
WILDMAN:
Based on Archimedes' evidence,

41:20.128 --> 41:22.328
Hiero convicts the goldsmith
of fraud

41:22.330 --> 41:24.463
and has the swindler executed.

41:24.465 --> 41:28.935
♪♪

41:28.937 --> 41:31.604
Today, an ancient Greek
golden wreath,

41:31.606 --> 41:33.973
like the one tested
by Archimedes,

41:33.975 --> 41:37.476
is on display at the
Museum of Fine Arts, Houston.

41:37.478 --> 41:39.412
It recalls the ancient genius

41:39.414 --> 41:41.948
who found his
crowning achievement

41:41.950 --> 41:43.750
in a bathtub of water.

41:43.752 --> 41:48.021
♪♪

41:48.023 --> 41:50.489
From a nuclear nightmare

41:50.491 --> 41:53.059
to a Tinseltown scandal,

41:53.061 --> 41:55.261
a Eureka moment

41:55.263 --> 41:57.263
to history's longest duel --

41:57.265 --> 41:58.498
I'm Don Wildman,

41:58.500 --> 42:00.600
and these are the
"Mysteries at the Museum."
